On 7/10/07, James Treanor <jtreanor10(-at-)hotmail.com> wrote:
>
>  Before you do anything else, give Petronix a call and ask a tech what the
> nominal voltage is to keep from damaging your ignitor.  Whenever I'm working
> with electrical other than ignition, I disconnect the hot wire to the coil,
> you can fry your ignitor if you don't.  I would also recommend that if you
> have a 009 handy to keep it as a spare with points and condensor and
> hold-down bracket allready timed, just pop in and keep going
> If you set up a seperate relay, be sure it's continuous duty, like the
> relay for a Westie aux battery.  IMHO, finding the problem with the stock
> harness is your best and cheapest bet.  When wires fail it is generally at
> the exposed ends, not in the middle of the harness, barring external damage
> from road debris or wrecks.  If you soldered [SIC?] in a section of new wire
> from the wire bundle to the coil in the engine compartment with new ends I
> bet the problem would go away.
>
> Also, don't forget to spin your fuses!
